\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-607\li607\sl240\slmult1\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\tx7280\tx7840\tx8400\tx8960\tx9520 1) pp. 13 WATER RESTRICTIONS /\'85PROVING SOCIAL AWARENESS EFFECTIVENESS\'85\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\highlight7 Data indicates that water consumption was reduced by around 13.6% during Level 1 restrictions (compared with 4% to 6% as estimated in the LHWP) and by around 21% during the short period of Level 2 restrictions (compared with 7% to 9% as estimated in the LHWP). Overall, the reduction was 14.3% for the period covering both Level 1 and 2 restrictions. A 3% reduction had already been observed over the 12 months leading into restrictions. This was during a period where customers were exposed to water saving messages as part of the Love Water campaign pp.13 \par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Water restrictions should continue to form a part of the drought response in the Lower Hunter. Future changes to the restrictions program should be guided by NSW Government\rquote s investigations into options for a more consistent approach to water restrictions across NSW. It is noted that water savings in future droughts may be more difficult to achieve due to the possible impact of \lquote demand hardening\rquote  ( TEH REDUCTION IN THE ABILITY OF A CUSTOMER TO ARCHIEVE further water reduction after easier and more cost-effective water reductions have been implemented).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\highlight0 See also p.16 for more info\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}IMPORTANT: Overall community feedback was that conservation of water should be encouraged early in times of drought to slow down the usage rate. They also felt water restrictions and education were important as drought continues to avoid running out of water. The positive aspects raised by participants were that water restrictions (see more pp.16-17)\par

